TULAREMIA, IMPORTED HARES - ITALY (02)
**************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Tularemia, hares - Northern Italy 980108231642
Date: Fri, 09 Jan 1998 12:38:38 +0100
From: Pasquale Urbano <micro@CESIT1.UNIFI.IT>

>[I have no problem with this but as the hares "had been released" before
>they were found to be "tularemia-infected", how do we know that these were
>not domestic Italian dead hares? Were the imported Hungarian hares tatooed
>or ear-notched or ear-tagged? Was this area previously hare-free? What was
>the basis for this epidemiological decision? - Mod.MHJ
One point I may clarify: tularemia was diagnosed in 4 animals sampled out
of the actual shipment. The shipment was released before the sampled
animals were found to be infected.
The rest must be inferred from the short press release. My educated guess
is that the area was considered to be tularemia-free; that hares had to be
imported [by hunters' organizations for replenishing the local population;
that the finding of dead hares in the area was considered to be the
consequence of the recent introduction of infected animals into the area.
I am confident that the vet service is tackling the problem, and I am eager
to learn how it is moving, and the information it is gathering.
I am at loss in identifying the 'epidemiological decision' to which the
moderator refers when wondering on which basis it was taken. If he refers
to the letter alerting the local family doctors about the risk of tularemia
in humans, I may inform that [human tularemia is a nationally notifiable
disease in Italy. I gather from
<http://www.sanita.interbusiness.it/malinf/BollEpid/1996/tula.htm> that in
1996 there were 0 cases in the province of Pavia (much larger that the
Voghera district), 10 cases in the whole of Italy. My opinion is that it
is well to alert physicians when the risk of a rare disease becomes more
than remote.
If I were a family doctor in the USA. I would welcome an alert from an
agency which has spotted the importation of potential sources of tularemia
in my area.
Note: I am almost sure that the newspaper referred to the common European
hare, _Lepus timidus_; I would not think of them as domestic animals.
--
Pasquale Urbano
