[Thanks to Pasquale we now know some of the background to the initial
identification of (4) infected hares. One wonders why the animals were
released before the laboratory results were available.
As to "the rest" which our member has inferred, can we have a more
authoritative statement from someone with specific knowledge, which was the
intent of my original comment. Inference and reality are two very separate
things, especially in epidemiology.
It is important to know whether the "dead hares ... in the area" were from
[A the positive released shipment or whether [B they were from the
pre-existing local population in Voghara (= "domestic Italian hares" of my
original note) ... my mistake, I forget that British English and Global
English are two different languages) reflecting either [B.1 a pre-existing
but only now realised local condition or [B.2 that the infection had
spread from the recently imported Hungarian hares into a previously
infection-free local Voghara hare population. Three importantly different
situations. The suggestion from the original news report was Hypothesis
B.2, which may be true but I still question if only to get reliable
information. That the imported shipment of hares was infected is not in
doubt. Has anyone "fingerprinted" these various isolates?
It was obviously wise to warn the local physicians, and with which I have
and had no quibbles. - Mod.MHJ
